sentences: Stephen Dennis Thompson (born 24 April 1952) is a British musician, songwriter and record producer who is responsible for a number of single and album chart hits and well known songs recorded by international recording artists.
In 1969, he formed the band Bullfrog who established a huge reputation in the North East of England and then further afield.
In 1973 the band signed to Cube Records and started work with Black Sabbath producer Rodger Bain.
In 1978 he joined Impulse Studios in Wallsend, Tyne and Wear, England.
Initially recordings were released in an Impulse subsidiary Rubber Records but in 1979 he helped set up a new record label "Neat Records".
This and other anecdotes (including the source of the marching sounds on Rock Until You Drop) are revealed in Thompson's interviews for Ravens 2013 DVD, "Rock Until You Drop, A Long Days Journey".
In 1980 Thompson re-established his acquaintance with Bullfrog's first producer Roger Bain.
Thompson eventually quit Neat Records in 1981.
In 1982, he enjoyed a top 20 hit with a recording by Wavelength of his song "Hurry Home".
In late 1982, Pete Waterman signed Thompson to an exclusive songwriting deal with MCA Music Publishing.
In the summer of 1982, plans were well under way for the recording of the Tygers next album (to be called The Cage), when John Sykes suddenly quit the band.
In 1982, Sheena Easton released her Madness, Money & Music album which contained the Steve Thompson song "Please Don't Sympathise".
In 1983, Thompson wrote English lyrics for the Italian Eurovision Song Contest Per Lucia by Riccardo Fogli.
In 1983, Celine Dion recorded the same song (Please Don't Sympathise) and with a French adaptation by Eddie Marnay it was released as "Ne me plaignez pas" on her album Les chemins de ma maison.
A music video was made in 1984, for the Sur les chemins de ma maison TV special.

In 1984, Thompson once again joined forces with Gus Dudgeon who brought the legendary Dick James (the man who signed the Beatles) out of retirement to sign Steve to an exclusive songwriting agreement with DJM (Dick James Music)
Thompson wrote or co-wrote several tracks Verity's 1985 release "The Truth of The Matter" and also appears on the credits for keyboards and bass.
The song became a finalist in the 1986 Song For Europe
